Chapter 1
Kollen
It was 4:30 in the morning according to Itrania time. Kollen hated getting up so early. Mainly because he had to wake up the rest of his platoon. He quietly got out of bed, put on his combat uniform, strapped on his assault vest, and gathered his things from the storage cabinet, carefully picking up a particularly small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with all necessary gear, including a respirator, goggles, and other required items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he slipped out of the barracks, his boots crunching on the mud and ice.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and another pocket held a cigarette. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff, then opened the door. Over the past week, he had to use every trick in the book to wake his subordinates. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, as it barely worked half the time, producing only a faint hissing sound through the speakers.
"Time to wake them up?" Kollen turned around when Lieutenant Nemich approached.
"Yes." Kollen replied.
"What method do you plan to use this time?"
Before Kollen could answer, the door opened and Harris, Cres, and several others hurried out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Cres said.
"What woke you up?" Kollen asked.
"Firstly, we really don't want to see what method you will use to wake everyone up today. Secondly, the first team to get up can enjoy breakfast first," answered a soldier named Ravelik. "You know how terrible those breakfasts are."
Colen said, "You're right, Sergeant Ravelik." He reached out and pressed the switch. The camp suddenly erupted with piercing alarms. He heard people shouting inside, accompanied by a chaotic rush of footsteps.
"Oh my god, Varturi," Nemich said. "I thought they should have learned to wake up with you by now."
"My new recruits did," Colen pointed at Harris, Kres, and Ravelik. "But to be fair, their platoon leader and squad leaders always make sure to wake up before the soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company ran out. They were all dressed and ready. Some new recruits looked groggy, while others seemed very frustrated.
"Good morning, everyone," Kollen said cheerfully.
"To be honest, sir, why are you waking us up that way?" asked a grunt (a private).
"Because ordinary alarms are just trash. And Daybreak never sleeps late," Kollen replied.
"Take your personal belongings," Kollen continued. As a captain and deputy commander of the platoon, he had the responsibility to assist Lieutenant Obralin Shao in overseeing and leading the platoon. "We won't be back. Senior NCOs and lieutenants, give your men and yourselves 15 minutes to do final checks and bring today's rations."
Members of Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the Second Group Army's Second Assault Brigade. Before merging, they were originally two separate companies, Cohort and Dagger. This was a elite company, and Kollen felt complex emotions about being promoted to captain, with many reasons.
Kollen and Captain Nymich walked side by side down the brightly lit paths of the base, where most of the lights were powered by generators and mostly red, helping them avoid enemy bombers. To strike back, Daybreak had begun using the "Weasel" tactic both in the air and on the ground.
“A new day, a new mission for Hell's Vanguard,” Nymich said with a dry laugh. “Where are they going to send us this time?”
“Some frontline base outside Ianros City. We're being sent to support the ground offensive.” Kollen said, taking a puff on his cigarette. He blamed Cress for getting him hooked on smoking, but considering the year they'd had—endless battles—he let it go.
“That’s bad. The front lines are tight,” Nymich whispered. “Why not support Holland’s front line instead of always aiding the Kurgan front?”
“Agreed, brother.” Kollen said, flicking his cigarette butt into the mud. “We’ll walk with the First Armored Platoon; we won’t have to march. Captain Xiao should be there.”
"Is Captain Shao going to drive us?" Nymich asked, surprised.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I thought. I mean, he's not great, but he's not someone you'd want to dislike either."
Kollen raised his thumb and index finger, pressing the microphone against his throat, and shifted his backpack onto his back. "Exodus Company, all units, assemble at the west vehicle depot after completing your missions. We will depart together with the First Armored Platoon at 05:00."
Every few seconds, he received responses from the squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Cress, and Lark were lower-ranking NCOs. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them have been good friends. Kollen feels like he knew them a long time ago, even though it has only been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since the former platoon leader was retired one week ago after being hit by a Daybreak sniper, Cress has been leading the second squad.
As they approached the vehicle depot, Kollen and Nymich's eyes fell upon approximately eight Kronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were moving around, ensuring that their war machines were in top condition. Kollen quickly found Lieutenant Obralin Shao among the crowd, who was talking with the commander of the armored platoon. When they approached, Shao looked at them briefly before coming forward; there was no discernible emotion on his usually cold face.
"Lieutenant Nymich... Lieutenant Valteri..." he said, slowing his pace. Captain Xia looked at Colonel Ren's holster, then raised his head. "Should the platoon already be ready?"
